¹ aliquando. I have ventured to insert aliquando in the text in addition to the vulgate unum denique aliquod. The use of uuum aliquod is of course common enough in Cicero: ‘a single one': cp. in Verr. ii. 1, ἓ 62; Div. ἓ 27; pro Sest. ξ 19. So also ξ 185 below, unum aliquem nominatim. The addition of aliquando may be defended as introducing the clement of time in addition to quam pecuniam, unde, and quem ad modum. Palaeographically the occurrence of aliquid in s before profectae, and the omission of aliquod in Str, may be held to justify the suggestion of aliquando.
